{
  "texts": [
    "The fibre sequence, 𝐷 𝑑 ℎ S -→ 𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S -→ 𝑃 𝑑-1 ℎ S, splits rationally.",
    "Moreover,𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S [𝑒 -1 𝑑] ≃ 𝐷 𝑑 ℎ S 𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S [(1 -𝑒 𝑑) -1] ≃ 𝑃 𝑑-1 ℎ S.Proof.",
    "We may split 𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S using the idempotents𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S ≃ 𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S [𝑒 -1 𝑑] × 𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S [(1 -𝑒 𝑑) -1].Consider the first term of this splitting and the induced fibre sequence𝐷 𝑑 ℎ S [𝑒 -1 𝑑] -→ 𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S [𝑒 -1 𝑑] -→ 𝑃 𝑑-1 ℎ S [𝑒 -1 𝑑], By Theorem 6.1 we know the last term is zero, so the first map is an equivalence.",
    "By Theorem 6.2 we know that 𝐷 𝑑 ℎ S [𝑒 -1 𝑑] ≃ 𝐷 𝑑 ℎ S. A similar argument for the other term of the splitting shows that𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S [(1 -𝑒 𝑑) -1] ≃ 𝑃 𝑑-1 ℎ S [(1 -𝑒 𝑑) -1] ≃ 𝑃 𝑑-1 ℎ S.□We can now apply our knowledge of how the idempotent acts on the homogeneous fibre sequence (2) of the monoidal unit to identify the pieces of the splitting on the level of ∞categories.Theorem 6.4.",
    "There is an equivalenceExc 𝑑 * (Sp 𝜔, Sp) Q ≃ 1≤𝑖≤𝑑 Homog 𝑖 (Sp 𝜔, Sp) Q, of ∞-categories.Proof."
  ]
